# Git & GitHub workflow

## Relationship to other rules

Coding and project context: **`gpxmapper-core.mdc`**, **`python-standards.mdc`**. This file is **git-only** (commits, branches, PRs) and is the **only** project rule for commit message format (no separate commit-message rule file).

## Commit message rules

Commits use a **Commitizen-friendly subject** (so `cz changelog` / `cz bump` can parse the first line) and carry the **Jira work item in the body**, which also matches how Jira scans commit messages for links.

### Subject line (first line, mandatory)

- **Conventional only:** `<type>(<scope>): <short summary>`
- **Do not** put `[PROJ-123]` on the subject line — that breaks Commitizen’s default `commit_parser` / `changelog_pattern` (they expect `feat`, `fix`, … at the start).
- `scope` is optional; `!` before `:` is allowed for breaking changes.
- Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `perf`, `build`, `ci`, `bump`, `revert` (see `scripts/check_commit_message.py`).

Style: imperative mood, no period at the end of the subject, keep the summary concise.

### Body (after one blank line, mandatory for normal commits)

1. **Blank line** immediately after the subject (empty line — no spaces).
2. **Issue line:** `[<KEY>-<number>]: <issue title>` — Jira-style key in **brackets**, then colon, space, and a short human-readable title (from Jira or aligned with the branch).
3. **Details:** bullet list or short paragraphs describing what changed.

Example:

```text
feat(geolocate): add sqlite-backed reverse geocode cache

[GPXM-1]: Nominatim reverse geolocation for overlays
- add cache module and CLI wiring
- document env and local Docker helpers
```

### Tooling

- **`pre-commit`** runs **`scripts/check_commit_message.py`** on the `commit-msg` stage (`uv run pre-commit install --hook-type commit-msg`).
- **Commitizen** (same hook run) validates the subject with its default conventional rules; **`.cz.toml`** keeps normal `allowed_prefixes` (`Merge`, `Revert`, …) only — no ticket prefix on the subject.
- Derive `<KEY>-<number>` from the branch when possible (e.g. `GPXM-1-nominatim-…` → `[GPXM-1]: …`).

Exempt first lines (no body rules): `Merge `, `Revert `, `Pull request`, `fixup!`, `squash!`, `amend!`.

## Branch naming conventions

- Use kebab-case (lowercase with hyphens)
- Follow the pattern: `<type>/<issue-number>-<short-description>` or `<issue-number>-<short-description>`
- Types: feature, bugfix, hotfix, release, support
- Example: `feature/123-add-dark-mode`, `PROJECT-123-add-dark-mode`

## Pull request guidelines

- Link related issues using keywords (Fixes #123, Closes #456)
- Provide a clear description of changes
- Add screenshots for UI changes
- Ensure all CI checks pass before requesting review
- Keep PRs focused and small when possible
